WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.350 --> 00:00:04.496
NULL:  Every gap, every shortcut, every forgotten door -

2
00:00:04.496 --> 00:00:05.765
I will find it.

3
00:00:06.065 --> 00:00:08.935
VEGA:  Not tonight. Welcome to the Aegis Citadel. I'm

4
00:00:08.935 --> 00:00:10.745
Vega, and I'll be your guide.

5
00:00:11.045 --> 00:00:15.641
Every modern organization runs on information. Protect it,

6
00:00:15.641 --> 00:00:18.653
and you thrive. Lose it, and you fall.

7
00:00:19.703 --> 00:00:23.263
VEGA:  Picture an organization's information as a walled city.

8
00:00:23.263 --> 00:00:25.463
At its heart sits the Crown Data -

9
00:00:25.463 --> 00:00:29.023
the records, secrets, and services everyone depends on.

10
00:00:29.323 --> 00:00:32.453
NULL:  I don't want your walls. I want what

11
00:00:32.453 --> 00:00:35.844
they guard - the Crown Data. And trust?

12
00:00:35.844 --> 00:00:38.018
Trust shatters so easily.

13
00:00:38.318 --> 00:00:41.266
NOVA:  I'm Nova - just started here, and honestly?

14
00:00:41.266 --> 00:00:43.323
I'm new to all of this. Can we

15
00:00:43.323 --> 00:00:45.380
start from the very beginning?

16
00:00:45.680 --> 00:00:48.691
VEGA:  We will. First, a few words everyone uses

17
00:00:48.691 --> 00:00:50.600
and almost no one defines.

18
00:00:51.650 --> 00:00:54.272
NOVA:  Okay, so who writes all this stuff?

19
00:00:54.572 --> 00:00:56.771
VEGA:  That would be NIST. Think of them as

20
00:00:56.771 --> 00:00:59.092
the standards lab for digital defense.

21
00:01:00.142 --> 00:01:02.742
VEGA:  The thing we're protecting is an information system.

22
00:01:03.042 --> 00:01:05.344
NOVA:  So... not just a computer?

23
00:01:05.644 --> 00:01:08.684
VEGA:  Far more. The people and processes count too.

24
00:01:09.734 --> 00:01:11.236
NOVA:  And a 'control' is...?

25
00:01:11.536 --> 00:01:15.986
VEGA:  A safeguard. Something deliberate that reduces risk. NIST

26
00:01:15.986 --> 00:01:19.266
SP 800-53 is a giant, organized catalog of

27
00:01:19.266 --> 00:01:19.656
them.

28
00:01:20.706 --> 00:01:23.848
NOVA:  People keep throwing around this word, 'risk.'

29
00:01:24.148 --> 00:01:26.964
VEGA:  Risk is likelihood times impact. A threat is

30
00:01:26.964 --> 00:01:29.716
who or what could hurt you; a vulnerability

31
00:01:29.716 --> 00:01:32.212
is the weakness they'd use; risk is the

32
00:01:32.212 --> 00:01:34.196
chance - and the cost - if they

33
00:01:34.196 --> 00:01:34.388
do.

34
00:01:35.438 --> 00:01:38.683
VEGA:  Every control in the catalog serves three goals.

35
00:01:38.683 --> 00:01:40.238
Remember them as C-I-A.

36
00:01:40.538 --> 00:01:43.947
VEGA:  Confidentiality - keep secrets secret. Integrity - keep

37
00:01:43.947 --> 00:01:47.108
data correct and untampered. Availability - keep it

38
00:01:47.108 --> 00:01:48.658
working when you need it.

39
00:01:48.958 --> 00:01:54.180
NOVA:  Confidentiality, Integrity, Availability. The reason every guardian exists.

40
00:01:55.230 --> 00:01:57.812
NOVA:  But why does any of this even exist?

41
00:01:58.112 --> 00:02:00.676
VEGA:  A law says you must protect systems. A

42
00:02:00.676 --> 00:02:03.578
catalog lists what you can use. A framework

43
00:02:03.578 --> 00:02:05.872
is the process that connects them.

44
00:02:06.172 --> 00:02:09.016
VEGA:  The law is FISMA - the Federal Information

45
00:02:09.016 --> 00:02:12.672
Security Modernization Act. 800-53 is the catalog. The

46
00:02:12.672 --> 00:02:15.584
RMF is the process. Hold those three apart,

47
00:02:15.584 --> 00:02:17.412
and everything else clicks.

48
00:02:18.462 --> 00:02:20.804
NOVA:  Isn't privacy just part of security?

49
00:02:21.104 --> 00:02:24.011
VEGA:  They overlap, but they aim at different things.

50
00:02:24.011 --> 00:02:27.042
In Revision 5, security and privacy finally share

51
00:02:27.042 --> 00:02:27.784
one catalog.

52
00:02:28.834 --> 00:02:32.376
NOVA:  So this 'eight-hundred fifty-three' everyone keeps citing -

53
00:02:32.376 --> 00:02:33.336
what even is it?

54
00:02:33.636 --> 00:02:37.290
VEGA:  A catalog. A giant, well-organized menu of controls

55
00:02:37.290 --> 00:02:38.436
you put to work.

56
00:02:39.486 --> 00:02:42.429
VEGA:  The catalog is organized into twenty families. We'll

57
00:02:42.429 --> 00:02:44.806
walk them as twenty districts of the city.

58
00:02:45.106 --> 00:02:47.568
VEGA:  A district isn't really a place - it's

59
00:02:47.568 --> 00:02:51.195
a family of related safeguards: policies, processes, and

60
00:02:51.195 --> 00:02:52.426
technical controls.

61
00:02:52.726 --> 00:02:55.628
NOVA:  Twenty? That's a lot of ground.

62
00:02:55.928 --> 00:02:58.128
VEGA:  So we'll group them into six layers of

63
00:02:58.128 --> 00:03:00.848
defense. By the end, you'll remember every one.

64
00:03:01.898 --> 00:03:04.920
VEGA:  Every control shares the same anatomy. Learn it

65
00:03:04.920 --> 00:03:06.978
once, and you can read them all.

66
00:03:07.278 --> 00:03:10.211
VEGA:  First the identifier, like AC-6 - the family

67
00:03:10.211 --> 00:03:11.078
and a number.

68
00:03:11.378 --> 00:03:14.482
VEGA:  Then the control itself: the requirement, what you

69
00:03:14.482 --> 00:03:15.538
must actually do.

70
00:03:15.838 --> 00:03:17.900
NOVA:  And the discussion explains it?

71
00:03:18.200 --> 00:03:21.234
VEGA:  It gives context and rationale - helpful, but

72
00:03:21.234 --> 00:03:22.920
not itself a requirement.

73
00:03:23.220 --> 00:03:28.143
VEGA:  Related controls point to neighbors. Enhancements add strength

74
00:03:28.143 --> 00:03:31.875
- AC-6(1) is an enhancement of AC-6. References

75
00:03:31.875 --> 00:03:33.940
point outside the catalog.

76
00:03:34.990 --> 00:03:38.710
VEGA:  Here's a single control. AC-6, Least Privilege.

77
00:03:39.010 --> 00:03:42.565
NOVA:  Clean. An ID, a title, and what it

78
00:03:42.565 --> 00:03:43.192
means.

79
00:03:44.242 --> 00:03:46.651
VEGA:  When you see a gold card, the Archivist

80
00:03:46.651 --> 00:03:49.246
is reading the catalog's real words - word

81
00:03:49.246 --> 00:03:49.802
for word.

82
00:03:50.102 --> 00:03:53.817
ARCHIVIST:  Employ the principle of least privilege, allowing only

83
00:03:53.817 --> 00:03:57.463
authorized accesses for users (or processes acting on

84
00:03:57.463 --> 00:04:00.834
behalf of users) that are necessary to accomplish

85
00:04:00.834 --> 00:04:02.898
assigned organizational tasks.

86
00:04:03.948 --> 00:04:06.810
NOVA:  People keep saying 'baseline' - what's that mean?

87
00:04:07.110 --> 00:04:09.809
VEGA:  A starting kit of controls - Low, Moderate,

88
00:04:09.809 --> 00:04:11.630
or High, sized to the stakes.

89
00:04:12.680 --> 00:04:15.293
NOVA:  Wait, hold on - where'd the Low, Moderate,

90
00:04:15.293 --> 00:04:16.662
and High baselines go?

91
00:04:16.962 --> 00:04:19.847
VEGA:  Sharp eye. In Revision 5 they moved out,

92
00:04:19.847 --> 00:04:22.082
into a companion book: 800-53B.

93
00:04:22.382 --> 00:04:27.401
800-53 is the catalog of controls. 800-53B holds

94
00:04:27.401 --> 00:04:31.270
the baselines and tailoring guidance.

95
00:04:32.320 --> 00:04:35.310
VEGA:  800-53 doesn't stand alone. It plugs into a

96
00:04:35.310 --> 00:04:38.440
process called the Risk Management Framework.

97
00:04:38.740 --> 00:04:41.419
VEGA:  In plain terms: prepare, decide how much the

98
00:04:41.419 --> 00:04:44.402
system matters, pick controls, put them in place,

99
00:04:44.402 --> 00:04:46.837
check they work, get a leader to approve

100
00:04:46.837 --> 00:04:48.420
it, then watch it forever.

101
00:04:48.720 --> 00:04:51.946
NOVA:  And the catalog is 800-53; the baselines in

102
00:04:51.946 --> 00:04:55.622
800-53B help choose which controls we start with.

103
00:04:55.922 --> 00:04:58.308
VEGA:  We'll walk all seven steps in Act Two.

104
00:04:58.308 --> 00:05:00.568
For now, just know the catalog has a

105
00:05:00.568 --> 00:05:00.882
home.

106
00:05:01.932 --> 00:05:03.780
Three guides ride with you.

107
00:05:04.080 --> 00:05:06.855
NULL:  ...and one rides against you.

108
00:05:12.232 --> 00:05:14.911
VEGA:  Six layers lie ahead. The Outer Walls. The

109
00:05:14.911 --> 00:05:17.272
Watchtowers. The Keepers of the Pact.

110
00:05:17.572 --> 00:05:20.452
VEGA:  The High Council. The Forge. The Vaults and

111
00:05:20.452 --> 00:05:23.132
Lifelines. Then the finale: Siege Night.

112
00:05:24.182 --> 00:05:26.590
One honest note before we ride out.

113
00:05:26.890 --> 00:05:29.430
VEGA:  The story is ours. The control text is

114
00:05:29.430 --> 00:05:31.770
theirs - real, and shown on screen.

115
00:05:32.820 --> 00:05:35.938
VEGA:  Let's make it stick. What's a control? Pause,

116
00:05:35.938 --> 00:05:36.700
and answer.

117
00:05:37.000 --> 00:05:40.125
In plain terms, a security 'control' is best

118
00:05:40.125 --> 00:05:41.048
described as:

119
00:05:41.348 --> 00:05:44.827
Your options. A. A type of computer. B.

120
00:05:44.827 --> 00:05:48.931
A safeguard that reduces risk. C. A government

121
00:05:48.931 --> 00:05:49.556
agency.

122
00:05:49.856 --> 00:05:52.758
NOVA:  Pause here and lock in your answer.

123
00:05:59.808 --> 00:06:02.656
VEGA:  The answer is B. A safeguard that reduces

124
00:06:02.656 --> 00:06:05.991
risk. A control is a safeguard or countermeasure

125
00:06:05.991 --> 00:06:08.423
- it reduces risk to the system and

126
00:06:08.423 --> 00:06:09.048
its data.

127
00:06:10.098 --> 00:06:12.999
NOVA:  Quick check. Where do the baselines live now?

128
00:06:12.999 --> 00:06:14.160
Pause, and answer.

129
00:06:14.460 --> 00:06:17.567
Where do the Low, Moderate, and High control

130
00:06:17.567 --> 00:06:18.908
baselines live now?

131
00:06:19.208 --> 00:06:24.689
Your options. A. In 800-53 itself. B. In

132
00:06:24.689 --> 00:06:28.936
NIST SP 800-53B. C. In the RMF.

133
00:06:29.236 --> 00:06:32.138
NOVA:  Pause here and lock in your answer.

134
00:06:39.188 --> 00:06:41.989
VEGA:  The answer is B. In NIST SP 800-53B.

135
00:06:41.989 --> 00:06:45.178
In Revision 5 the Low, Moderate, and High

136
00:06:45.178 --> 00:06:49.068
baselines moved out into companion volume 800-53B.

137
00:06:50.118 --> 00:06:52.238
VEGA:  And how many families guard our city?

138
00:06:52.538 --> 00:06:56.748
How many control families does 800-53 Revision 5

139
00:06:56.748 --> 00:06:57.186
have?

140
00:06:57.486 --> 00:07:01.734
Your options. A. Twelve. B. Seventeen. C. Twenty.

141
00:07:02.034 --> 00:07:04.936
NOVA:  Pause here and lock in your answer.

142
00:07:11.986 --> 00:07:15.358
VEGA:  The answer is C. Twenty. Revision 5 organizes

143
00:07:15.358 --> 00:07:17.906
its controls into twenty families.

144
00:07:18.956 --> 00:07:22.228
NOVA:  Notebook open. That's the whole map on one

145
00:07:22.228 --> 00:07:22.618
page.

146
00:07:22.918 --> 00:07:26.076
VEGA:  That's your foundation. Next, we ride for the

147
00:07:26.076 --> 00:07:26.918
Outer Walls.

148
00:07:27.218 --> 00:07:29.073
NULL:  I'll be waiting at the gate.
